Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{0.5%tsp}. Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Pour a large glug of @oil{} into a #roasting tray{}. Pop it onto the top shelf of your oven to warm up.

Put a small drizzle of @oil{1%drizzle} in the bottom of another #roasting tin{}. Snip the string holding the @whole British chicken{1} together, remove and discard. Pop the chicken in the tin and drizzle with @oil{}. Sprinkle over half the @dried thyme{1%tsp}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast on the middle shelf of your oven for ~{60-75%minutes} depending on size.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when the juices from the thigh run clear.

Once the chicken is cooked, rest it wrapped in #foil{} for ~{15-20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel the @potatoes{900%g}, chop into 4cm chunks. Add them to the boiling water and cook until the edges have softened when you poke them with a knife, ~{7-8%minutes}. Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, pop back into the pan, sprinkle on the remaining thyme and half the @plain flour{24%g}. Give your pan a shake to fluff up the potato.

When the chicken has 45 mins left to cook, take your hot #baking tray{} out of your oven, carefully transfer your potatoes onto it in a single layer. Sprinkle over a pinch of @salt{} and gently toss the potatoes in the oil. Roast the potatoes on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{45-50%minutes}, turn halfway through cooking.

Wash your saucepan and fill with water again. Bring to the boil on high heat. Peel the @swede{1}(peeled) and chop into 2cm chunks. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop the @hazelnuts{40%g}(roughly chopped). Once the water is boiling, add the swede and simmer until tender, ~{25-30%minutes}.

> TIP: The swede is cooked when you can easily slip a knife through it.

Once cooked, drain in a colander, pop back in the pan and cover with a #lid{}. Set aside.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{1%drizzle} in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat. Once hot, add the @chopped cavolo nero{200%g} and fry until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Then add the garlic, a handful of @baby spinach{125%g} and a splash of @water{}. Stir until wilted, keep adding handfuls of spinach until it's all wilted. Add a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch} and cook until the water has evaporated, then stir in the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} and half the @creme fraiche{75%g}. Gently bring to the boil, then remove from the heat and leave to the side (we will reheat later).

Meanwhile, pop a saucepan on medium heat and add half the @unsalted butter{15%g}, allow to melt, stir in the remaining flour. You've made a roux! Cook until the roux is a medium brown colour and gradually stir in the @water{400%ml}, @chicken stock paste{1} and any chicken resting juices. Bring to the boil, stirring out any lumps that form. Lower the heat and simmer until the gravy has thickened to your liking, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Once the swede is cooked, drain and put it back in the pan, add the remaining @unsalted butter{15%g} and @creme fraiche{75%g}, season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Mash vigorously with a #potato masher{} until it resembles a rough mash. Cover with a lid and leave to the side.

Once everything is ready, reheat the greens, swede and gravy if you need to. Carve the chicken. Share the veggies and spuds between your plates. Arrange the chicken alongside. Sprinkle the hazelnuts over the creamed greens. Add any chicken resting juice or water to the gravy to get it to your desired consistency. Pour the gravy over the chicken and dig in!

> TIP: Be careful when adding the chicken juices to the gravy, the more you add the thinner the gravy will be.